Caleb McDougall Monk There are two key things on my resume that I feel would contribute to your company. Firstly my time travelling and volunteering. I recently spent six months travelling and volunteering from Colombia down to Brazil. In this time I had the opportunity to live and work with locals, picking up conversational Spanish and learning how to fit into different communities. I enjoyed having responsibilities such as self-management, organising travel plans, forming friendships with a variety of individuals, participating in charity programs (hearing aids & community clothing/food) and general community jobs. I loved the opportunity of living with locals and forming worldwide friendships and the common understandings that came along with the new experiences. I also appreciated the difficulties faced and time I spent out of my comfort zone, specifically how as I overcame challenges I felt more comfortable travelling autonomously, with flexibility and effective time management. Additionally, I have experience in Public Health work, the most influential work I have contributed to would be through my placement with the Townsville Public Health Unit (TPHU). This work greatly aided in my understanding of the functioning of a healthcare unit, particularly the simultaneously unique but interconnected roles of each section. I learned about the professional standards set to promote safe environments and the impact that projects and legislations have on this role. I developed knowledge on the current chronic and acute issues that affect health, nationally and locally. I picked up new skills such as entomology identification, statistical processes, insights into communicable diseases, the importance of community engagement and the tracking of notifiable conditions nationally. I attended field and lab sessions that improved my understanding of how to act and contribute to these skills. I learned about how changes to policy have changed the functioning of public health units and how important national policies and funding are to effective implementation programs. Crucially I got to experience the importance of ethical awareness in public health, with the need for confidentiality in individuals information, and the different requirements needed from health practitioners in Indigenous communities. Overall I believe this work helped me understand the fundamental processes used to create tangible solution-oriented results, and as a result, would make me a good fit for you. points.text: There are two key things on my resume that I feel would contribute to your company. Firstly my time travelling and volunteering. I recently spent six months travelling and volunteering from Colombia down to Brazil. In this time I had the opportunity to live and work with locals, picking up conversational Spanish and learning how to fit into different communities. I enjoyed having responsibilities such as self-management, organising travel plans, forming friendships with a variety of individuals, participating in charity programs (hearing aids & community clothing/food) and general community jobs. I loved the opportunity of living with locals and forming worldwide friendships and the common understandings that came along with the new experiences. I also appreciated the difficulties faced and time I spent out of my comfort zone, specifically how as I overcame challenges I felt more comfortable travelling autonomously, with flexibility and effective time management. Additionally, I have experience in Public Health work, the most influential work I have contributed to would be through my placement with the Townsville Public Health Unit (TPHU). This work greatly aided in my understanding of the functioning of a healthcare unit, particularly the simultaneously unique but interconnected roles of each section. I learned about the professional standards set to promote safe environments and the impact that projects and legislations have on this role. I developed knowledge on the current chronic and acute issues that affect health, nationally and locally. I picked up new skills such as entomology identification, statistical processes, insights into communicable diseases, the importance of community engagement and the tracking of notifiable conditions nationally. I attended field and lab sessions that improved my understanding of how to act and contribute to these skills. I learned about how changes to policy have changed the functioning of public health units and how important national policies and funding are to effective implementation programs. Crucially I got to experience the importance of ethical awareness in public health, with the need for confidentiality in individuals information, and the different requirements needed from health practitioners in Indigenous communities. Overall I believe this work helped me understand the fundamental processes used to create tangible solution-oriented results, and as a result, would make me a good fit for you.
